[{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Read each question carefully. Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of three point charges that are arranged such that they form the corners of an equilateral triangle. The point charge in the lower left corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the lower right corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the upper middle corner is shaded gray and has a charge of positive 3 Q. The distance from the point charge in the upper middle corner to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled d. Point P is located at the midpoint between the two point charges that form the horizontal base of the triangle, directly below the point charge in the upper middle corner. The distance from point P to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled the fraction d over 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598177.g13.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Three point charges are brought from very far away and placed at the corners of an equilateral triangle with sides of length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>. The top point charge has a charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive 3 Q\"><math alttext=\"positive 3 Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span>, and each of the point charges located on the base of the triangle has a charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative 2 Q\"><math alttext=\"negative 2 Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span>. Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span> is located at the midpoint of the base of the triangle, as shown. Express all algebraic answers in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Derive an expression for the work required to assemble the charges in the configuration shown.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) Derive an expression for the magnitude of the electric field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) On the following charge configuration, draw a Gaussian surface that would have the maximum amount of net electric flux enter or exit its surface.<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of three point charges that are arranged such that they form the corners of an equilateral triangle. The point charge in the lower left corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the lower right corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the upper middle corner is shaded gray and has a charge of positive 3 Q. The distance from the point charge in the upper middle corner to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled d. Point P is located at the midpoint between the two point charges that form the horizontal base of the triangle, directly below the point charge in the upper middle corner. The distance from point P to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled the fraction d over 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598177.g14.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Derive an expression for the electric potential at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Ei part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ei\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) A positive test charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase q\"><math alttext=\"lowercase q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>q</mi></math></span></span> is placed at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>.</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. On the following diagram, draw an arrow to indicate the direction of the net force exerted on the test charge. The arrow should start on, and point away from, the dot. <span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></p></li></ul><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a black dot at the intersection of two perpendicular dashed lines. One dashed line is horizontal, and the other dashed line is vertical.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598177.g15.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Eii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Eii\"><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span>ii. The locations of the point charges at the top and bottom right corner of the triangle are switched, as shown in the following diagram.<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></p></li></ul><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of three point charges that are arranged such that they form the corners of an equilateral triangle. The point charge in the lower left corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the lower right corner is shaded gray and has a charge of positive 3 Q. The point charge in the upper middle corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The distance from the point charge in the upper middle corner to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled d. Point P is located at the midpoint between the two point charges that form the horizontal base of the triangle, directly below the point charge in the upper middle corner. The distance from point P to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled the fraction d over 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598177.g16.svg\"/></div><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span><span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span><span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span><span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span>Does the direction of the net force on the test charge change? If the direction changes, indicate the direction of the new net force, and justify your answer. If the direction does not change, justify your answer.</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Fi part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Fi\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(f) The charges are returned to their initial positions. <span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. On the following diagram, put an “<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>x</mtext></math></span></span>” at a location where an additional negative charge could be placed so the net force on the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive 3 Q\"><math alttext=\"positive 3 Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> charge would be zero.<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span><span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></p></li></ul><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of three point charges that are arranged such that they form the corners of an equilateral triangle. The point charge in the lower left corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the lower right corner is shaded black and has a charge of negative 2 Q. The point charge in the upper middle corner is shaded gray and has a charge of positive 3 Q. The distance from the point charge in the upper middle corner to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled d. Point P is located at the midpoint between the two point charges that form the horizontal base of the triangle, directly below the point charge in the upper middle corner. The distance from point P to each point charge in the lower corners is labeled the fraction d over 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598177.g17.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"},{"id":"VR598177","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Fii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Fii\"><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. Explain your reasoning for the location indicated in part (f)(i).</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598177_rubric"}]